An analysis on feminine vernacular in 21st century American music

Michael Waldron

Introduction

WARNING: THIS PROJECT FOCUSES ON AND CONTAINS EXPLICIT LANGUAGE, READER DISCRETION IS ADVISED

I made this project to study word choice when referring to women in song lyrics. Specifically, I wanted to see how those word choices differ between musical genres and over time. While my analysis wont go too in-depth (at least for now) one sub-goal of this project is to illustrate how prevalent misogynistic language is in music today. I intend to compare the use of such harsh language to more acceptable phrases.

One important caveat is this analysis will be on the frequency of words that are traditionally feminine and/or used in reference to women. Meaning, I have not implemented any sort of algorithm to detect whether saying bitch in a song has been directed towards a man or a woman. Each instance of bitch will be counted, because culturally, if an individual calls a man a bitch it is intended to emasculate that man, thus conveying the same message as using the insult against a woman: being feminine makes you weak/lesser.

As I collect the word frequency data, I will include terms that are gender neutral such as babe and baby. Since many of the songs are written by female artists, one can assume many instances of gender neutral terms will be in reference to men. Therefore, all my analyses will be two-fold: with and without gender neutral terms.

Getting and cleaning the data

The lyric data we will be using can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/gyani95/380000-lyrics-from-metrolyrics/data. It is a repository of approximately 380,000 songs and their lyrics distinguished by title, year, artist, and genre.

After loading the .csv, the data frame needs to be cleaned up a bit. I got rid of all the songs before the year 2000 as I want to focus on 21st century music. I then converted all text to lowercase so future pattern matching would be easier. To improve readability I replaced all - with a space in the song and artist columns. Then, I removed all carriage return characters as these arent part of the songs, but from the lyric website itself. I also removed all songs without lyrics and/or valid genres as they wont be very helpful. Finally, I removed all punctuation characters to once again make pattern matching easier.

lyrics_raw <- read_csv("C:/Users/Michael/OneDrive/Professional/Projects/Women in Music/lyrics.csv", col_types = list(col_integer(), col_character(), col_integer(), col_character(), col_character(), col_character()))
lyrics_readable <- lyrics_raw[,-1] %>%
  filter(year >= 2000) %>%
  mutate_at(c("song", "artist", "genre", "lyrics"), funs(tolower(.))) %>%
  mutate_at(c("song", "artist"), funs(gsub("-", " ", .))) %>%
  mutate_at(c("lyrics"), funs(gsub("\n", " ", .)))

unique(lyrics_readable$genre)
##  [1] "pop"           "hip-hop"       "not available" "other"        
##  [5] "rock"          "metal"         "country"       "jazz"         
##  [9] "electronic"    "folk"          "r&b"           "indie"
lyrics_improved <- lyrics_readable %>%
  filter(genre != "other") %>%
  filter(genre != "not available") %>%
  drop_na()
lyrics_df <- lyrics_improved %>%
  mutate_at(c("lyrics"), funs(gsub("[[:punct:]]","",.)))
head(lyrics_df, n = 1)

counts_tidy <- counts_sum %>%

Exploratory data analysis

Now that the collection process is complete, lets see what the data can tell us. Also, because the data collection is skewed (not the same number of songs per genre nor per year), we will need to observe percentages of total phrases observed as opposed to raw frequency.

counts_tidy %>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  summarize(frequency = sum(frequency)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = word, y = frequency)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_text(aes(x = word, y = frequency, label = frequency, vjust = -0.5)) +
  ggtitle("Frequency of all phrases across the entire data set") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

gendered_df <- counts_tidy %>%
  filter(word != "shawty") %>%
  filter(word != "baby") %>%
  filter(word != "darling") %>%
  filter(word != "honey") %>%
  filter(word != "sweetheart") %>%
  group_by(genre) %>%
  mutate(genre_total = sum(frequency))

gendered_df <- gendered_df %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  mutate(year_total = sum(frequency))

gendered_df <- gendered_df %>%
  group_by(year, genre) %>%
  mutate(year_genre_total = sum(frequency))
  
neutral_df <- counts_tidy %>%
  filter(word != "shawty") %>%
  group_by(genre) %>%
  mutate(genre_total = sum(frequency))

neutral_df <- neutral_df %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  mutate(year_total = sum(frequency))

neutral_df <- neutral_df %>%
  group_by(year, genre) %>%
  mutate(year_genre_total = sum(frequency))

neutral_df %>%
  group_by(word, genre, genre_total) %>%
  summarize(frequency = sum(frequency)) %>%
  mutate(percent_of_total = 100*(frequency/genre_total)) %>%
  filter(word != "b___h") %>%
  filter(word != "c__t") %>%
  filter(word != "s__t") %>%
  filter(word != "shawty") %>%
  filter(word != "w___e") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = word, y = percent_of_total, fill = genre)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = "dodge") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of appropriate language by genre")

  group_by(word, year, genre, year_genre_total) %>%
  summarize(frequency = sum(frequency)) %>%
  mutate(percent_of_total = 100*(frequency/year_genre_total)) %>%
  filter(word != "chick") %>%
  filter(word != "female") %>%
  filter(word != "girl") %>%
  filter(word != "lady") %>%
  filter(word != "sister") %>%
  filter(word != "woman") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = percent_of_total, color = word)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(~genre) +
  ggtitle("Distribution of harsh language by genre and over time - excluding gender neutral terms") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Discussion

I cant say Im particularly surprised, but I am definitely still disappointed in what the data shows. Using the difference between the gender neutral inclusive and exclusive results as a range, we can come to several conclusions. In hip-hop music, more than half of all references to women are either bitch or whore. In metal music, at least 5% of the references are cunt. In the early 2000s, specifically, between 60 and 70 percent of the references in metal were whore alone. The early 2000s were also quite an angry time for electronic artists it seems. Furthermore, as time goes on, the language across all genres is getting worse, especially in the frequency of bitch. Finally, to end on a somewhat lighter note, not all of the most common words are so vitriolic, thanks to the popularity of baby and girl.

While I personally believe that nothing should be off limits for art, everything in art should have a purpose, especially if what is included is harsh, shocking, controversial, etc. It is safe to say that most of the instances of harsh language in these songs do not serve a purpose, do not convey a deeper meaning, but are weapons in one of two ways. The first is obvious: a direct insult intended to do harm by objectifying women, reducing women to animals, or (as previously stated) implying a man is lesser for acting like a woman. The second is both more common, and honestly much more dangerous: when words like bitch are simply used to replace girl or woman without any ulterior motive directly attached to the word. These replacements are worse because they are lazy writing that keep misogyny very much alive in American culture by normalizing hate speech.

We need to do a better job teaching boys to respect women. Not only this, but we need to teach them to give respect for the right reasons. Dont tell boys they need to respect women because women are fragile and need protection. Dont tell boys they need to respect women because happy wife, happy life. Tell boys to respect women, because women are people and therefore deserve your respect on a fundamental level. We also need female artists to step-up and fight against misogynistic language in music, both by refusing to participate themselves and refusing to work with artists who are a part of the problem.

I wont sit here and type away as though I have all the answers, but what I do know is misogyny is perceived as so normal today that the President of the United States can say moved on her like a bitch grab them by the pussy and not be held accountable. Not only was Trump not held accountable, but his campaign was able to convince millions of Amerians that his statements werent misogynistic, but simply locker room talk aka boys being boys. While I dont know all the answers, I know we can and need to do better.

Id like to end on a positive note, so I will share a short & simple phrase that has been lingering in my mind since I heard it a few weeks ago: Its chaos, be kind (Patton Oswalt/Michelle McNamara).
